article.description:
Cappie Pondexter and Diana Taurasi each scored 30
points to lead the Phoenix Mercury to their first win of the
season, a 90-76 victory Tuesday night over the defending champion
Sacramento Monarchs.
article.headline: Pondexter, Taurasi each drop 30 as Mercury get year's first win
article.linkText: Pondexter, Taurasi each drop 30 as Mercury get year's first win
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- New Phoenix coach Paul Westhead was supposed to
bring a running style to the Mercury. They finally showed it
Tuesday night.

Cappie Pondexter and Diana Taurasi each scored 30 points, and
Phoenix outshot and outrebounded the defending champion Sacramento
Monarchs in a 90-76 victory Tuesday night for its first victory of
the year.

"As the players and I have said, we knew we were getting
better," Westhead said. "So it wasn't like we all of a sudden did
a total reversal."

Pondexter keyed a 14-5 run with eight points to start the second
half, helping the Mercury (1-4) to a 63-41 lead. The Monarchs never
got closer than 16.

"We knew it was going to come," Pondexter said. "We didn't
know when, but we had a feeling it was going to come soon. We
played amazing. We played together, we rebounded together. We did a
lot of good things."

Phoenix scored 16 points on the fast break, had 21 assists as a
team, got the lead early and held it.

"We did run the break better tonight," Westhead said. "We
kicked it out better but that was really because we played better
defense. We were getting the ball off the miss and that really
helps fastbreak basketball."

Yolanda Griffith scored 21 points and had seven rebounds to lead
the Monarchs (3-3). Nicole Powell added 18 points and seven
rebounds.

"The biggest thing is we didn't defend," Sacramento assistant
coach Tom Abatemarco said. "We gave up too many points. They ran
their stuff real well. They got the ball to Pondexter and Taurasi,
and Taurasi was terrific. That's the kind of player she is, she was
just absolutely dynamite."

Abatemarco ran the team Tuesday night in place of head coach
John Whisenant, who didn't make the trip due to a family illness.

Kamila Vodichkova had 13 points and 14 rebounds for Phoenix.
Taurasi added eight rebounds and four assists. Sacramento beat the
Mercury 105-78 in the team's season opener May 20.

"We want to turn it around here in Phoenix and we know we can
do it," said Pondexter, the No. 2 overall pick from Rutgers.
"We've got the right pieces. We've just got to continue to jell
and get together."

After scoring eight points in the opener, Pondexter has averaged
28.5 points a game in the other four contests.

Phoenix made 30-of-48 (62.5 percent) field goals through three
quarters after failing to shoot better than 46 percent in its first
four games. The Mercury finished the game 34-of-64 (53.1 percent).

The Mercury also held Sacramento to 40 percent shooting
(28-of-70) and outrebounded the bigger Monarchs 35-32, including 30
defensive rebounds.

"Whenever you can rebound with a team like this you have a
chance to win," Taurasi said. "That was key."

In the first half, Taurasi scored 18 points and Pondexter added
13 to help the Mercury take a 49-36 lead at the break.

"A lot of it is getting used to each together," Taurasi said.
"We are still trying to find out who we are."
